ing.%3Cp%3ECSIS%2FChina%20Power%2FAirbus%20DS%202024%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20combination%20of%20two%20major%20Chinese%20shipyards%20to%20build%20Changxing%20Island%20is%20the%20%26quot%3Bclearest%20sign%26quot%3B%20of%20one%20of%20China's%20biggest%20strengths%20in%20shipbuilding%2C%20said%20Matthew%20Funaoile%2C%20a%20senior%20fellow%20with%20CSIS'%20China%20Power%20Project%2C%20explaining%20that%20%26quot%3BChina%20is%20finding%20ways%20to%20continue%20to%20be%20more%20efficient%20and%20more%20productive%2C%20and%20it's%20leveraging%20its%20industrial%20capability%20to%20modernize%20its%20navy.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EChina%20calls%20its%20Changxing%20Island%20operation%20a%20%26quot%3Bshipbuilding%20base%2C%26quot%3B%20and%20recent%20satellite%20images%20have%20shown%20substantial%20shipyard%20construction.%20It's%20also%20building%20new%20ships.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20first%20Yulan-class%20assault%20ship%2C%20which%20features%20a%20catapult%20launching%20system%20for%20fixed-wing%20aircraft%2C%20is%20being%20built%20there.%20Once%20it's%20complete%2C%20this%20vessel%2C%20known%20as%20the%20Type%20076%2C%20will%20be%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fchinas-unusual-assault-ship-was-rapidly-built-purpose-a-mystery-2024-8%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ethe%20largest%20amphibious%20assault%20ship%20in%20the%20world%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%228ed9745e-c7a1-4b5d-8c35-023aa1cc85da%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EMore%20than%20warships%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%225280%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Several%20ships%20are%20under%20construction%20at%20a%20shipbuilding%20enterprise%20in%20the%20Taicang%20Port%20Economic%20and%20Technological%20Development%20Zone%20in%20Suzhou%2C%20Jiangsu%20province%2C%20China%2C%20on%20July%2015%2C%202024.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F66eae9c6cfb7f307e572a1ae%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22